{"title_page": "Franco Costanzo", "text_new": "{{short description|Argentine football goalkeeper|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name= Franco Costanzo\n|image= Franco Costanzo 5875.jpg\n| image_size = 150px\n|fullname= Franco Costanzo Geymonat\n|height={{convert|1.88|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|df=yes|1980|9|5}}\n| birth_place = [[R\u00edo Cuarto, C\u00f3rdoba|R\u00edo Cuarto]], [[Argentina]]\n|position=[[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub= \n| clubnumber= \n|youthyears1=\n|youthclubs1=\n|years1=1998\u20132005\n|years2=2005\u20132006\n|years3=2006\u20132011\n|years4=2011\u20132012\n|years5=2013\u20132017\n|clubs1=[[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]\n|clubs2=[[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]]\n|clubs3=[[FC Basel]]\n|clubs4=[[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n|clubs5=[[Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]]\n|caps1= 87  |goals1= 0\n|caps2= 31  |goals2= 0\n|caps3= 141 |goals3= 0\n|caps4= 6   |goals4= 0\n|caps5= 44  |goals5= 0\n| totalcaps      = 309 |totalgoals = 0\n|nationalyears1=1999\n|nationalyears2=2003\n|nationalteam1=[[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina U-20]]\n|nationalteam2=[[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]\n|nationalcaps1= 4 |nationalgoals1= 0\n|nationalcaps2= 1 |nationalgoals2= 0\n|pcupdate= 15 October 2017\n|ntupdate=12 December 2010\n}}\n\n'''Franco Costanzo Geymonat''' (born 5 September 1980) is an [[Argentina|Argentine]] football [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] who plays for Chilean club [[CDUC|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]] of the [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de Chile|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]].\n\nHe has earned the reputation of being an eccentric goalkeeper by often dribbling the ball past the opposition's strikers and by making somewhat unorthodox saves. Early in his career, Costanzo was once considered an excellent prospect; however, due to a few lengthy injuries, he has only recently managed to fulfill his full potential.\n\n==Club career==\nCostanzo started playing professionally with [[Buenos Aires]] giants [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate]] in 2000 and made his first-team debut in 2001. He had become the first choice goalkeeper by 2002 and was looked upon by many as one of the most talented goalkeepers in South America. However, injury started to plague him and when he returned from the sidelines, [[Germ\u00e1n Lux]] had established himself as River Plate's Number 1. His search for first-team action then took him to [[La Liga|Spain's La Liga]] as he transferred to [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s]] in 2005. He was first choice at Alav\u00e9s straight away, but when they were relegated into the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]], he asked the manager, [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Salmer\u00f3n]], to be put on the transfer list.\n\n[[Swiss Super League|Swiss side]] [[FC Basel]] acquired his services in July 2006 for \u00a31.4 million after the departure of veteran goalkeeper [[Pascal Zuberb\u00fchler]]. His Basel career did not get off to a great start; he made a blunder in his first match against [[FC St. Gallen]] on 30 July 2006 in the 3\u20132 away defeat. However, he played excellent in the second half of the [[2006\u201307 Swiss Super League|2006\u201307 season]] and was voted the ''FCB Player of the Year''. He earned much praise during the [[2007\u201308 Swiss Super League|2007\u201308 season]] for his form as Basel became Champions and especially for his part in helping the team earn a valuable [[UEFA Cup]] away point against [[NK Dinamo Zagreb]] in the hostile atmosphere of the [[Maksimir Stadium]] on 8 November 2007.\n\nOn 17 July 2008, the day before the [[2008\u201309 Swiss Super League]] season kicked off, he was named Basel [[Captain (association football)|captain]] and he signed a new contract until 2011.<ref>[http://baz.ch/news/index.cfm?ObjectID=3176855D-1422-0CEF-7007690A54FFC1A7 Basler Zeitung, 17 July 2008]  {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> His first game as captain was on 18 July 2008, in a 2\u20131 win over [[BSC Young Boys]] at the [[Stade de Suisse, Wankdorf]], in which he was named Man of the Match.\n\nOn 9 August 2009, Costanzo and teammate [[Beg Ferati]] were involved in a scuffle after a 1\u20131 with [[FC Z\u00fcrich]]. The pair began arguing on the pitch, and then Ferati shoved Costanzo who responded by pulling Ferati's hair. Other players then pulled them apart before the situation escalated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.101greatgoals.com/when-teammates-fight-franco-costanzo-vs-beg-ferati-fc-basel/33195/ |title=When teammates fight: Franco Costanzo vs Beg Ferati (FC Basel) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707054908/http://www.101greatgoals.com/when-teammates-fight-franco-costanzo-vs-beg-ferati-fc-basel/33195/ |archivedate=7 July 2011 }}</ref> Costanzo was fined by the club and given a three match ban by the [[Swiss Football Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/10082009/58/international-football-costanzo-fined-hair-pull.html |title=Costanzo fined for hair pull |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815001919/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/10082009/58/international-football-costanzo-fined-hair-pull.html |archivedate=15 August 2009 }}</ref>\n\nCostanzo played for FC Basel for five years, in which time they won the [[Swiss Cup]] three times and the national [[Swiss Super League|Championship]] also three times. He also played twice in the Champions League group-stages in the 2008\u201309 season and the 2010/\u201311 season where FC Basel did a couple of huge sensations like the draw in the Nou Camp in Barcelona where they tied 1\u20131 or in the Stadio Olimpico in Rome where they beat AS Roma 3\u20131. During this period he played 141 league games, including cup and international games he had over 200 club appearances. He played his last match for the team on 25 May 2011 and was substituted out in the 87th minute to a standing ovation. He was replaced by his designated successor [[Yann Sommer]].\n\nOn 9 June 2011, it was revealed that Costanzo came to an agreement with Greek champions [[Olympiacos FC]] for a three-year contract. Six months later, on 26 January 2012, Costanzo's contract was terminated by mutual consent.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.olympiacos.org/en/article/7576/olympiacos-announces-termination-contract-franco-costanzo | title = Olympiacos announces termination of contract with Franco Costanzo | publisher = [[Olympiacos FC]] | date = 26 January 2012 | accessdate = 2 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 May 2012, Costanzo retired from professional football without saying clearly the reason of his decision.\n\nOn 29 June 2013, Costanzo returned to [[association football|football]] signing for [[Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]] a one-and-a-half-year contract.\n\n==International career==\nCostanzo was an Argentine international at Under-20 level, and was part of the [[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina squad]] that took part at the [[1999 FIFA World Youth Championship]]. At senior level, he made his only main team appearance in [[Argentina national football team|Argentina's]] 4\u20132 [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2006 World Cup Qualifying]] win over [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] at the [[River Plate Stadium]] on 9 October 2004.<ref>{{NFT player|id=316|accessdate=2 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCostanzo is married to Carla. The couple have three children. Their two daughters are named Emma and Zoe and their son named Ciro was born on 24 May 2011.<ref name=\"sport.ch\">{{cite web | url = http://sport.ch.sportalsports.com//sportch/generated/article/tnt_fussball/2011/05/24/15397000000.html | title = FCB-Costanzo zum dritten Mal Vater geworden  | publisher = sport.ch | date = 24 May 2011 | language = German| accessdate = 2 November 2013}}</ref> All three children were born in Basel.\n\n==Honours==\n\n;[[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]\n*[[Primera Division Argentina]]: Clausura 2002, Clausura 2003, Clausura 2004\n\n;[[FC Basel]]\n*[[Swiss Super League]]: [[2007\u201308 Swiss Super League|2007\u201308]], [[2009\u201310 Swiss Super League|2009\u201310]], [[2010\u201311 Swiss Super League|2010\u201311]]\n*[[Swiss Cup]]: [[2006\u201307 Swiss Cup|2006\u201307]], [[2007\u201308 Swiss Cup|2007\u201308]], [[2009\u201310 Swiss Cup|2009\u201310]]\n\n;[[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n*[[Superleague Greece]]: [[2011\u201312 Superleague Greece|2011\u201312]]\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[2011\u201312 Greek Football Cup|2011\u201312]]\n\n;[[Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]]\n* [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de Chile]]: Clausura 2015\u201316, Apertura 2016-17\n* [[Supercopa de Chile]]: 2016\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Soccerway}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mhRCkcdU0RA&mode=related&search=Cupfinal%202007%20Costanzo Franco Costanzo on YouTube]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070426111638/http://es.sports.yahoo.com/fo/profiles/23477.html Franco Costanzo profile on Yahoo Deportes] {{in lang|es}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.fcb.ch/sport/show/playerDetailByID/27580/72/9/36 |title=Profile at FC Basel |language=de |website=fcb.ch |access-date=31 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080714213037/http://www.fcb.ch/sport/show/playerDetailByID/27580/72/9/36 |archive-date=14 July 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n* [http://www.football.ch/sfl/777819/de/Kader.aspx?pId=709181 Profile at Swiss Football League Website] {{in lang|de}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box|title=[[FC Basel]] captain|before=[[Ivan Ergi\u0107]]|after=[[Marco Streller]]|years=2008\u20132011}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Universidad Cat\u00f3lica squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Costanzo, Franco}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from R\u00edo Cuarto, C\u00f3rdoba]]\n[[Category:Argentine footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentina youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentina under-20 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentina international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Alav\u00e9s players]]\n[[Category:River Plate footballers]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:FC Basel players]]\n[[Category:Olympiacos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica footballers]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Swiss Super League players]]\n[[Category:Chilean Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Chile]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Chile]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Argentine football goalkeeper|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name= Franco Costanzo\n|image= Franco Costanzo 5875.jpg\n| image_size = 150px\n|fullname= Franco Costanzo Geymonat\n|height={{convert|1.88|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|df=yes|1980|9|5}}\n| birth_place = [[R\u00edo Cuarto, C\u00f3rdoba|R\u00edo Cuarto]], [[Argentina]]\n|position=[[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub= \n| clubnumber= \n|youthyears1=\n|youthclubs1=\n|years1=1998\u20132005\n|years2=2005\u20132006\n|years3=2006\u20132011\n|years4=2011\u20132012\n|years5=2013\u20132017\n|clubs1=[[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]\n|clubs2=[[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]]\n|clubs3=[[FC Basel]]\n|clubs4=[[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n|clubs5=[[Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]]\n|caps1= 87  |goals1= 0\n|caps2= 31  |goals2= 0\n|caps3= 141 |goals3= 0\n|caps4= 6   |goals4= 0\n|caps5= 44  |goals5= 0\n| totalcaps      = 309 |totalgoals = 0\n|nationalyears1=1999\n|nationalyears2=2003\n|nationalteam1=[[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina U-20]]\n|nationalteam2=[[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]\n|nationalcaps1= 4 |nationalgoals1= 0\n|nationalcaps2= 1 |nationalgoals2= 0\n|pcupdate= 15 October 2017\n|ntupdate=12 December 2010\n}}\n\n'''Franco Costanzo Geymonat''' (born 5 September 1980) is an [[Argentina|Argentine]] football [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] who plays for Chilean club [[CDUC|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]] of the [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de Chile|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]].\n\nHe has earned the reputation of being an eccentric goalkeeper by often dribbling the ball past the opposition's strikers and by making somewhat unorthodox saves. Early in his career, Costanzo was once considered an excellent prospect; however, due to a few lengthy injuries, he has only recently managed to fulfill his full potential.\n\n==Club career==\nCostanzo started playing professionally with [[Buenos Aires]] giants [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate]] in 2000 and made his first-team debut in 2001. He had become the first choice goalkeeper by 2002 and was looked upon by many as one of the most talented goalkeepers in South America. However, injury started to plague him and when he returned from the sidelines, [[Germ\u00e1n Lux]] had established himself as River Plate's Number 1. His search for first-team action then took him to [[La Liga|Spain's La Liga]] as he transferred to [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s]] in 2005. He was first choice at Alav\u00e9s straight away, but when they were relegated into the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]], he asked the manager, [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Salmer\u00f3n]], to be put on the transfer list.\n\n[[Swiss Super League|Swiss side]] [[FC Basel]] acquired his services in July 2006 for \u00a31.4 million after the departure of veteran goalkeeper [[Pascal Zuberb\u00fchler]]. His Basel career did not get off to a great start; he made a blunder in his first match against [[FC St. Gallen]] on 30 July 2006 in the 3\u20132 away defeat. However, he played excellent in the second half of the [[2006\u201307 Swiss Super League|2006\u201307 season]] and was voted the ''FCB Player of the Year''. He earned much praise during the [[2007\u201308 Swiss Super League|2007\u201308 season]] for his form as Basel became Champions and especially for his part in helping the team earn a valuable [[UEFA Cup]] away point against [[NK Dinamo Zagreb]] in the hostile atmosphere of the [[Maksimir Stadium]] on 8 November 2007.\n\nOn 17 July 2008, the day before the [[2008\u201309 Swiss Super League]] season kicked off, he was named Basel [[Captain (association football)|captain]] and he signed a new contract until 2011.<ref>[http://baz.ch/news/index.cfm?ObjectID=3176855D-1422-0CEF-7007690A54FFC1A7 Basler Zeitung, 17 July 2008]  {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> His first game as captain was on 18 July 2008, in a 2\u20131 win over [[BSC Young Boys]] at the [[Stade de Suisse, Wankdorf]], in which he was named Man of the Match.\n\nOn 9 August 2009, Costanzo and teammate [[Beg Ferati]] were involved in a scuffle after a 1\u20131 with [[FC Z\u00fcrich]]. The pair began arguing on the pitch, and then Ferati shoved Costanzo who responded by pulling Ferati's hair. Other players then pulled them apart before the situation escalated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.101greatgoals.com/when-teammates-fight-franco-costanzo-vs-beg-ferati-fc-basel/33195/ |title=When teammates fight: Franco Costanzo vs Beg Ferati (FC Basel) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707054908/http://www.101greatgoals.com/when-teammates-fight-franco-costanzo-vs-beg-ferati-fc-basel/33195/ |archivedate=7 July 2011 }}</ref> Costanzo was fined by the club and given a three match ban by the [[Swiss Football Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/10082009/58/international-football-costanzo-fined-hair-pull.html |title=Costanzo fined for hair pull |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815001919/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/10082009/58/international-football-costanzo-fined-hair-pull.html |archivedate=15 August 2009 }}</ref>\n\nCostanzo played for FC Basel for five years, in which time they won the [[Swiss Cup]] three times and the national [[Swiss Super League|Championship]] also three times. He also played twice in the Champions League group-stages in the 2008\u201309 season and the 2010/\u201311 season where FC Basel did a couple of huge sensations like the draw in the Nou Camp in Barcelona where they tied 1\u20131 or in the Stadio Olimpico in Rome where they beat AS Roma 3\u20131. During this period he played 141 league games, including cup and international games he had over 200 club appearances. He played his last match for the team on 25 May 2011 and was substituted out in the 87th minute to a standing ovation. He was replaced by his designated successor [[Yann Sommer]].\n\nOn 9 June 2011, it was revealed that Costanzo came to an agreement with Greek champions [[Olympiacos FC]] for a three-year contract. Six months later, on 26 January 2012, Costanzo's contract was terminated by mutual consent.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.olympiacos.org/en/article/7576/olympiacos-announces-termination-contract-franco-costanzo | title = Olympiacos announces termination of contract with Franco Costanzo | publisher = [[Olympiacos FC]] | date = 26 January 2012 | accessdate = 2 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 May 2012, Costanzo retired from professional football without saying clearly the reason of his decision.\n\nOn 29 June 2013, Costanzo returned to [[association football|football]] signing for [[Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]] a one-and-a-half-year contract.\n\n==International career==\nCostanzo was an Argentine international at Under-20 level, and was part of the [[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina squad]] that took part at the [[1999 FIFA World Youth Championship]]. At senior level, he made his only main team appearance in [[Argentina national football team|Argentina's]] 4\u20132 [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2006 World Cup Qualifying]] win over [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] at the [[River Plate Stadium]] on 9 October 2004.<ref>{{NFT player|id=316|accessdate=2 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCostanzo is married to Carla. The couple have three children. Their two daughters are named Emma and Zoe and their son named Ciro was born on 24 May 2011.<ref name=\"sport.ch\">{{cite web | url = http://sport.ch.sportalsports.com//sportch/generated/article/tnt_fussball/2011/05/24/15397000000.html | title = FCB-Costanzo zum dritten Mal Vater geworden  | publisher = sport.ch | date = 24 May 2011 | language = German| accessdate = 2 November 2013}}</ref> All three children were born in Basel.\n\n==Honours==\n\n;[[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]\n*[[Primera Division Argentina]]: Clausura 2002, Clausura 2003, Clausura 2004\n\n;[[FC Basel]]\n*[[Swiss Super League]]: [[2007\u201308 Swiss Super League|2007\u201308]], [[2009\u201310 Swiss Super League|2009\u201310]], [[2010\u201311 Swiss Super League|2010\u201311]]\n*[[Swiss Cup]]: [[2006\u201307 Swiss Cup|2006\u201307]], [[2007\u201308 Swiss Cup|2007\u201308]], [[2009\u201310 Swiss Cup|2009\u201310]]\n\n;[[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n*[[Superleague Greece]]: [[2011\u201312 Superleague Greece|2011\u201312]]\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[2011\u201312 Greek Football Cup|2011\u201312]]\n\n;[[Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]]\n* [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de Chile]]: Clausura 2015\u201316, Apertura 2016-17\n* [[Supercopa de Chile]]: 2016\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.scoresway.com/?sport=soccer&page=player&id=11339 Scoresway.com Profile]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mhRCkcdU0RA&mode=related&search=Cupfinal%202007%20Costanzo Franco Costanzo on YouTube]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070426111638/http://es.sports.yahoo.com/fo/profiles/23477.html Franco Costanzo profile on Yahoo Deportes] {{in lang|es}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.fcb.ch/sport/show/playerDetailByID/27580/72/9/36 |title=Profile at FC Basel |language=de |website=fcb.ch |access-date=31 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080714213037/http://www.fcb.ch/sport/show/playerDetailByID/27580/72/9/36 |archive-date=14 July 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n* [http://www.football.ch/sfl/777819/de/Kader.aspx?pId=709181 Profile at Swiss Football League Website] {{in lang|de}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box|title=[[FC Basel]] captain|before=[[Ivan Ergi\u0107]]|after=[[Marco Streller]]|years=2008\u20132011}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Universidad Cat\u00f3lica squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Costanzo, Franco}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from R\u00edo Cuarto, C\u00f3rdoba]]\n[[Category:Argentine footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentina youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentina under-20 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentina international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Alav\u00e9s players]]\n[[Category:River Plate footballers]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:FC Basel players]]\n[[Category:Olympiacos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica footballers]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Swiss Super League players]]\n[[Category:Chilean Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Chile]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Chile]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "Pelmeen10", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franco_Costanzo"}
{"title_page": "41st United States Congress", "text_new": "{{Infobox United States Congress\n|number = 41st\n|image = USCapitol1877.jpg\n|imagename = [[United States Capitol]]\n|imagedate = 1877\n|start = March 4, 1869\n|end = March 4, 1871\n|vp = [[Schuyler Colfax]] (R)\n|pro tem = [[Henry B. Anthony]] (R)\n|speaker = [[James G. Blaine]] (R)\n|senators = 74\n|reps = 243\n|delegates = 9\n|s-majority = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|h-majority = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|sessionnumber1 = 1st \n|sessionstart1 = March 4, 1869\n|sessionend1 = April 10, 1869\n|sessionnumber2 = 2nd \n|sessionstart2 = December 6, 1869\n|sessionend2 = July 15, 1870\n|sessionnumber3 = 3rd \n|sessionstart3 = December 5, 1870\n|sessionend3 = March 4, 1871\n|previous = 40th\n|next = 42nd\n}}\nThe '''Forty-first United States Congress''' was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the [[United States Senate]] and the [[United States House of Representatives]]. It met in [[Washington, D.C.]] from March 4, 1869, to March 4, 1871, during the first two years of [[Presidency of Ulysses S. Grant|Ulysses S. Grant's presidency]]. The apportionment of seats in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] was based on the [[United States Census, 1860|Eighth Census of the United States in 1860]]. Both chambers had a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] majority.\n{{TOClimit|2}}\n\n==Major events==\n{{Main|1869 in the United States|1870 in the United States|1871 in the United States}}\n* March 4, 1869: [[Ulysses Grant]] became [[President of the United States]]\n* March 4, 1869: [[Carl Schurz]] R-Missouri became the first [[German American]] to serve in the [[United States Senate]]\n* May 10, 1869: [[Golden spike]] marked the completion of the [[First Transcontinental Railroad]] in [[Promontory, Utah]]<ref name=\"WDL\">{{cite web |url = http://www.wdl.org/en/item/11371/ |title = Ceremony at \"Wedding of the Rails,\" May 10, 1869 at Promontory Point, Utah |website = [[World Digital Library]] |date = 1869-05-10 |accessdate = 2013-07-21 }}</ref>\n* December 10, 1869: [[Wyoming Territory]] gave women the right to vote, one of the first such laws in the world\n* February 12, 1870: [[Utah Territory]] gave women the right to vote\n* February 25, 1870: Senator [[Hiram Rhodes Revels]] became the first African American ever to sit in the U.S. Congress\n\n==Major legislation==\n{{Main|List of United States federal legislation#41st United States Congress}}\n* March 18, 1869: [[Public Credit Act of 1869]], Sess. 1, ch. 1, {{USStat|16|1}}\n* April 10, 1869: [[Judiciary Act of 1869]], Sess. 1, ch. 22, {{USStat|16|44}}\n* May 31, 1870: [[Enforcement Act of 1870]], Sess. 2, ch. 114, {{USStat|16|140}}\n* June 22, 1870: An Act to establish the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]], Sess. 2, ch. 150, {{USStat|16|162}}\n* June 29, 1870: An Act to reorganize the [[Marine Hospital Service]], Sess. 2, ch. 169, {{USStat|16|169}}\n* July 12, 1870: [[Currency Act of 1870]], Sess. 2, ch. 252, {{USStat|16|251}}\n* July 14, 1870: [[Funding Act of 1870]], Sess. 2, ch. 256, {{USStat|16|272}}\n\n== Constitutional amendments ==\n* February 3, 1870: [[Fifteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifteenth Amendment]] was ratified by the requisite number of states (then 28) to become part of the Constitution<ref>{{cite web|last=Huckabee|first=David C.|title=Ratification of Amendments to the U.S. Constitution|url=http://www.au.af.mil/au/awc/awcgate/crs/97-922.pdf|work=[[Congressional Research Service reports]]|publisher=[[Congressional Research Service]], The [[Library of Congress]]|location=Washington D.C.|date=September 30, 1997}}</ref>\n\n== States readmitted ==\n* January 26, 1870: Virginia rejoined the Union\n* February 23, 1870: Mississippi rejoined the Union\n* March 30, 1870: Texas rejoined the Union\n* July 15, 1870: Georgia rejoined the Union, the last former Confederate state to be readmitted\n\n== Party summary ==\n\nThe count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this Congress, and includes members from vacancies and newly admitted states, when they were first seated. Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the \"Changes in membership\" section.\n\nDuring this Congress, [[Virginia]], [[Mississippi]], [[Texas]], and [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] were readmitted to representation.\n\n===Senate===\n{{USCongress Party summary\n| congress=41\n| party1=Democratic\n| party2=Republican\n| party3=Other\n| abb1=D\n| abb2=R\n\n| seats1_last=9\n| seats2_last=57\n| seats3_last=0\n| seats_vacant_last=8\n\n| seats1_begin=9\n| seats2_begin=57\n| seats3_begin=0\n| seats_vacant_begin=8\n| seats1_end=12\n| seats2_end=62\n| seats3_end=0\n| seats_vacant_end=0\n| seats1_next=16\n| seats2_next=55\n| seats3_next=1\n| note3_next=[[Liberal Republican Party (United States)|Liberal Republican]]\n| seats_vacant_next=2\n\n}}\n\n===House of Representatives===\n{{USCongress Party summary\n| congress=41\n| party1=Democratic\n| party2=Republican\n| party3=Conservative\n| party4=Other\n| abb1=D\n| abb2=R\n| abb3=C\n| seats1_last=45\n| seats2_last=170\n| seats3_last=2\n| seats4_last=3\n| note4_last=[[Independent Republican (United States)|Independent Republican]],<br/>& Conservative Republican \n| seats_vacant_last=23\n| seats1_begin=65\n| seats2_begin=149\n| seats3_begin=0\n| seats4_begin=0\n| seats_vacant_begin=29\n| seats1_end=67\n| seats2_end=167\n| seats3_end=5\n| seats4_end=0\n| seats_vacant_end=4\n| seats1_next=93\n| seats2_next=144\n| seats3_next=0\n| seats4_next=2\n| note4_next=[[Liberal Republican Party (United States)|Liberal Republican]] &<br/>[[Independent Republican (United States)|Independent Republican]]\n| seats_vacant_next=2\n\n}}\n\n==Leadership==\n[[File:Schuyler Colfax portrait.jpg|thumb|President of the Senate<br>[[Schuyler Colfax]]]]\n\n=== Senate ===\n* [[President of the United States Senate|President]] (R): [[Schuyler Colfax]]\n* [[President pro tempore of the United States Senate|President pro tempore]]: [[Henry B. Anthony]] (R)\n\n=== House of Representatives ===\n* [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker]]: [[James G. Blaine]] (R)\n* [[Republican Conference Chairman of the United States House of Representatives|Republican Conference Chair]]: [[Robert C. Schenck]] and [[Nathaniel P. Banks]]\n* [[Democratic Caucus Chairman of the United States House of Representatives|Democratic Caucus Chairman]]: [[William E. Niblack]] and [[Samuel J. Randall]]\n\n==Members==\nThis list is arranged by chamber, then by state. Senators are listed then by class and Representatives are listed then by district.\n:''[[#House of Representatives_3|Skip to House of Representatives]], below''\n\n===Senate===\nSenators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress. Preceding the names in the list below are [[Classes of United States Senators|Senate class numbers]], which indicate the cycle of their election. In this Congress, \"Class 1\" meant their term began in this Congress, facing re-election in 1874; \"Class 2\" meant their term ended in this Congress, facing re-election in 1870; and \"Class 3\" meant their term began in the last Congress, facing re-election in 1872.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Alabama|Alabama]] ====\n* 2. [[Willard Warner]] (R)\n* 3. [[George E. Spencer]] (R)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Arkansas|Arkansas]] ====\n* 2. [[Alexander McDonald (U.S. politician)|Alexander McDonald]] (R)\n* 3. [[Benjamin F. Rice]] (R)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from California|California]] ====\n* 1. [[Eugene Casserly]] (D)\n* 3. [[Cornelius Cole]] (R)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Connecticut|Connecticut]] ====\n* 1. [[William Alfr