ancis Preston Blair, Jr.|Francis P. Blair, Jr.]] (D)\n| January 20, 1871\n\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from Minnesota|Minnesota]] (2)\n| nowrap {{Party shading/Republican}} | [[William Windom]] (R)\n| Successor elected January 22, 1871.\n| nowrap {{Party shading/Republican}} | [[Ozora P. Stearns]] (R)\n| January 22, 1871\n\n|}\n\n=== House of Representatives ===\n*replacements: 14\n** [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]: 3 seat net loss\n** [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]: 3 seat net gain\n** [[Conservative Party of Virginia (1867)|Conservative Party of Virginia]]: no net change\n*deaths: 6\n*resignations: 6\n*contested election: 8\n*seats of newly re-admitted states: 17\n*'''Total seats with changes: 44'''\n<!--\nSorted Chronologically by date of vacancy\n-->\n{{See also|List of special elections to the United States House of Representatives}}\n{{Ordinal US Congress Rep}}\n|-\n| {{ushr|South Carolina|3|South Carolina 3rd}}\n| Vacant\n| style=\"font-size:80%\" | Contested election with [[J.P. Reed]]. Reed was never seated. House declared Hoge entitled to seat.\n| nowrap {{party shading/Republican}} | [[Solomon L. Hoge]] (R)\n| April 8, 1869\n|-\n| {{ushr|Wyoming Territory|AL|Wyoming Territory At-large}}\n| Vacant\n| style=\"font-size:80%\" | Territory organized in previous congress and remained vacant until December 6, 1869\n| nowrap {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Stephen Friel Nuckolls|Stephen F. Nuckolls]] (D)\n| December 6, 1869\n|-\n| {{ushr|Virginia|2|Virginia 2nd}}\n| rowspan=8 | Vacant\n| rowspan=8 style=\"font-size:80%\" | Virginia re-admitted into the Union\n| nowrap {{party shading/Republican}} | [[James H. Platt, Jr.]] (R)\n| rowspan=3 | January 26, 1870\n|-\n| {{ushr|Virginia|3|Virginia 3rd}}\n| nowrap {{party shading/Republican}} | [[Charles H. Porter]] (R)\n|-\n| {{ushr|Virginia|4|Virginia 4th}}\n| nowrap {{party shading/Conservative}} | [[George Booker]] (C)\n|-\n| {{ushr|Virginia|5|Virginia 5th}}\n| nowrap {{